  6  This file sets up a version of the Euclidean algorithm that works
  7  only with natural numbers.  Given a, b > 0, it computes the unique
  8  system (w, x, y, z, d) such that the following identities hold:
  9  
 10   w * z = x * y + 1
 11   a = (w + x) d
 12   b = (y + z) d
 13  
 14  These equations force w, z, d > 0.  They also imply that
 15  the integers a' = w + x = a / d and b' = y + z = b / d are coprime,
 16  and that d is the gcd of a and b.
 17  
 18  This story is closely related to the structure of SL₂(ℕ) (as a
 19  free monoid on two generators) and the theory of continued fractions.
 20  -/

 31   be thought of as representing the matrix
 32   [[w, x], [y, z]] = [[wp + 1, x], [y, zp + 1]]
 33   together with the vector [a, b] = [ap + 1, bp + 1].

214  /-- We can now define the full reduction function, which applies
215   step as long as possible, and then applies finish. Note that the

218   definition in terms of well-founded recursion.  The same fact
219   needs to be introduced in all the inductive proofs of properties
220   given below. -/
